  "What does Rolle's Theorem state?": "",
  "If f is continuous on [a,b], differentiable on (a,b), and f(a)=f(b), then there exists c in (a,b) with f'(c)=0": "",
  "The derivative of a polynomial is always zero somewhere": "",
  "Every continuous function has a zero derivative somewhere": "",
  "If f(a)=f(b), then f is constant": "",
  "Rolle's Theorem requires three conditions: continuity on [a,b], differentiability on (a,b), and equal endpoint values. The conclusion is f'(c) = 0 for some c in (a,b).": "",
  "What are the three conditions (hypotheses) of Rolle's Theorem?": "",
  "(1) f is continuous, (2) f has no asymptotes, (3) f is bounded": "",
  "(1) f is positive, (2) f is increasing, (3) f(a) = f(b)": "",
  "(1) f continuous on [a,b], (2) f differentiable on (a,b), (3) f(a) = f(b)": "",
  "(1) f is a polynomial, (2) f(a) = 0, (3) f(b) = 0": "",
  "The three hypotheses are: continuity on the closed interval, differentiability on the open interval, and equal function values at the endpoints.": "",
  "How is Rolle's Theorem related to the Mean Value Theorem?": "",
  "Rolle's Theorem is a special case of the MVT where f(a) = f(b)": "",
  "The MVT is a special case of Rolle's Theorem": "",
  "Rolle's Theorem applies to integrals": "",
  "They are completely different theorems": "",
  "When f(a) = f(b), the average rate of change is 0, so the MVT guarantees f'(c) = 0, which is exactly Rolle's conclusion.": "",
